Participant presented to ER after a fall on 07/19/2017. Participant stated she was on the phone with her son when she felt dizzy and fell down. Her son confirmed that he heard her fall. There was no loss of bowel or bladder and no loss of consciousness. There was no chest pain or shortness of breath. She hit her head when she fell and hit it a few additional times trying to get up. She was unable to get off the floor herself. She stated she does not normally fall. She lives at home alone in a 2 story house & goes up/down the stairs without difficulty. She has a walker but rarely uses it. After being admitted to the hospital, her work up came back negative. She had dizziness when she sat up. Her EKG showed inferolateral ST depressions. Her CT C-spine showed no acute spine fracture & CT of the head was negative. She was given gentle IVF hydration. She was alert and oriented x3. She was discharged on 07/20/2017 to a nearby nursing unit. She was told she cannot return home and needs skilled nursing. She was counseled about using her walker. Her son agreed with this and was referred to multiple agencies for help with this process.
AEOTHERHX: See narrative above. Participant has a history of falls and dizziness leading back to 2011. Although she has a walker, she rarely uses it. Because of the severity of this fall, the participant was discharged to a skilled nursing unit. She was told she cannot return home and needs skilled nursing and 24-hour care from now on. Her son agreed with this and was referred to multiple agencies for help with this process.

AEHEVNT: Multifocal infiltrating mixed lobular and ductal carcinoma, left breast
AEHCOMM: Participant’s mammogram on 07/12/2017 showed a small 6 MM speculated density in the upper outer quadrant of the left breast. She had a left lateral biopsy on her breast on 07/20/2017 and was diagnosed with recurrent invasive carcinoma, ER/PR positive and HER-2 negative by FISH. She was treated surgically with left breast wide local excision on 08/01/2017. Pathology showed multifocal infiltrating mixed lobular (85%) and ductal (15%) carcinoma, Nottingham Grade 3 (score 2 for tubule formation, 3 for nuclear atypia, and 3 for mitosis). DCIS is present. No necrosis of the invasive carcinoma was identified and it measured 2.6 X 2.6 X 3.0 CM. The participant had a left breast re-excision on 08/22/2017 which showed two foci of residual invasive mixed mammary carcinoma (largest focus measuring 12 MM) with 1 MM focal positive margin. Her oncologist prescribed her Anastrozole 1mg QD PO. More oncology records have been requested.

Pt entered the study in 2021 as cognitively normal, with subjective complaints about his memory that started in 2020. These complaints/issues didn't interfere with ADL and he had an MMSE score of 30 at this time. He gets easily distracted and appeared to have concentration problems. At a follow-up exam in 7/2022, his MMSE score decreased to 27, and his diagnosis was changed to amnestic MCI with a CDR of 0.5 questionable change. He was referred to our memory clinic in 12/2022 for decline in memory. After a full work-up, changes in Neurocognitive findings were essentially normal across all domains. This testing profile does not suggest a neurocognitive disorder at this time. Patient was referred out for a sleep study and was diagnosed with OSA in 04/2023(AE5) and has started using CPAP. He reports that his memory feels like it is improving, but he still has some subject complaints that we will continue to monitor.

AEOTHERHX: DMS 6/24/19 - Subject with PMH of GERD , HTN, hyperlipodemia presented to local ER with complaints of acute nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain. Pain began 2300 on 4/12/19. Initially attributed to "food poisoning"  but when pain persisted presented to ER. CT abdominal scan showed partial small bowel obstruction.  On exam epigastic and RUQ tenderness present. General surgery was contacted to place a nasogasrtric (NG) tube.  Prior to ER, at home had several episodes of nonbloody no bilious emesis. Had normal bowel movement about one hour after pain began. Was admitted for continued NG tube decompression and IV fluids.  By4/14/19 subject was passing flatus, denied nausea, emesis. NG tube with 1375 ml gastric content. Labs revealed no leukocytosis . H & H stable, electrolytes WNL. No evidence of acute kidney injury. NGT removed and started on clear liquids. Recieved pantoprazole IV for GERD while admitted and had prn zofran IV ordered. By 4/15/19 subject continued to improve. Felt well after breakfast. Labs and vitals were normal subject was discharged home.

Participant was initially evaluated by neurosurgery on 12/16/2020 with sudden onset of a severe headache. She was transferred to a higher-acuity hospital where head imaging revealed diffuse subarachnoid hemorrhage (see SAE #5), right posterior communicating artery aneurysm (See AE #8), and obstructive hydrocephalus. MRI from 25 Feb 2019 reveals a wedge shaped lesion with encephalomalacia and mild ex-vacuo hydrocephalus at the junction of the temporal and occipital lobes. There is no surrounding edema and only trace peripheral hemosiderin. The center of the lesion has imaging properties consistent with CSF, not blood. The lesion appears chronic. The participant probably had an emboli CVA somewhere between a couple of months to 15 months ago. Review of her risk factor and more aggressive secondary stroke prevention is quite reasonable.

Participant on statin & ASA.

After sleeping in, both caregiver, daughter, and participant went straight in to take shower together around 12:30 PM. After several minutes, in hot shower, participant complained of dizziness and fainted. Daughter caught her and lowered her down. Eyes were open, breathing normally, but unresponsive for about two minutes. Afterward, participant got up and was back to her baseline. Resumed usual activities and behavior for remainder of day. And since then, no recurrences. Given that participant was "back to normal" so quickly. Family did not seek medical attention. At the time: no slurred speech, no facial droop, no extremity weakness, numbness, or tingling. No chest pain or palpitations. No dyspnea. No recent illness. No fever or chills. No seizures. 
OF NOTE: Participant's usual routine is to get up between 6AM and 8AM and eat breakfast around 8 AM. On the day of the event, participant was drowsy and had not eaten or drank anything prior to taking a hot shower. This suggests vasovagal syncope.

Patient developed sepsis due to C. Difficile Colitis.  He was hospitalized from 10/10/2020 through 10/20/2020.  See full narrative below.
AEOTHERHX: Patient was brought to the emergency room from his care facility due to a fever of 102.1 on 29 Sep 2020.  Patient was also noted to have increased weakness and altered mental status. At that time pneumonia was suspected and treated as an outpatient with Augmentin twice per day.  However he returned to the hospital on 10 Oct 2020 and was admitted due to a fever and loose stools.  A week prior to admission patient started to have loose stools at least 2-3 times per day.  He had not been eating well and complained of some abdominal pain.  No vomiting, chest pains or shortness of breath.  Patient had a CT of the abdomen and pelvis revealing diverticulosis and moderate wall thickening of the sigmoid colon suggesting colitis or possibly diverticulitis.  He received IV fluids 2L, potassium for hypokalemia, and was given one dose of ceftriaxone and metronidazole for diverticulitis.  Stool sample was taken for C. Difficile.  C difficile panel came back positive.  Ceftriaxone was discontinued and patient was started on oral vancomycin. Patient was septic on admission secondary to the colitis with an elevated WBC count, hypokalemia and hypoalbuminemia, hypotension and acute kidney injury.  On discharge records the sepsis was noted to be secondary to C. Difficile colitis.  Patient’s diarrhea eventually improved.  Metronidazole was discontinued.  He was recommended to continue oral vancomycin until 10/25/2020.  He was discharged from the hospital on 10/20/2020.

GI bleed with associated coffee ground emesis, leukocytosis, acute kidney injury, lactic acidosis, myoglobinemia, diarrhea, resulting in patient's death.
AEOTHERHX: Patient began having coffee ground emesis during the evening of 6 June 2020.  Nursing home sent patient to emergency room and she was admitted to the hospital on 7 June 2020.  She was initially noted to be hypotensive with blood pressure of 70/37.  Lab work showed multiple derangements including leukocytosis, acute kidney injury, lactate 5.4 mmol/L, and myoglobin > 24,000.  She had non-bloody foul-smelling diarrhea.  She was given IV bolus fluids and had improvement in blood pressure.  Diagnosis was GI bleed due to suspected significant intra-abdominal pathology with main concern for ischemic bowel.  Lengthy discussion was had with patient's son/healthcare proxy who is at the bedside.  Due to patient's and sons wishes, decision was made to forego aggressive workup or management.  She was transitioned to comfort care measures including around the clock and as needed analgesia with Dilaudid, Ativan for restlessness, and Haldol for agitation.  Patient expired at 4:40 on 8 jun 2020.  Son called site at 8:38 on 8 Jun 2020 to report.

AE #2 Stage 1 Pancreatic Cancer:
1/24/2020 presented after 2½ days of painless jaundice, change in stool & urine color, itching, and decreased appetite.  Additionally, he reported intentional weight loss of 10-12 pounds since mid-December 2019.  Further evaluation indicated elevated bilirubin and elevated liver function tests.  MRCP was obtained which showed an approximately 2.5 cm mass in the head of the pancreas.  This was followed up with an endoscopic ultrasound, ERCP, and stent placement; at that time a biopsy was obtained which was consistent with adenocarcinoma.  An exploratory laparotomy was completed 2/19/2020 and was negative for any metastasis
Discontinued Claritin on 2/6/2020
Chemotherapy 2/24/2020 commenced with Folfirinox 5FU                   
(Admitted to hospital for SAE # 2)
3/17/2020 Chemotherapy continued – new drug Gemcitabine  Doses on 3/24, 4/14, 4/28, 5/12, 5/26, 6/24, 7/1, 7/15
6/24/2020-7/15/2020 Radiation: Pancreas: IMRT: 45 Gy in 15 fractions
8/19/2020 Surgical procedure: tumor resection
8/19/2020-9/16/2020 Hospitalization: Status post laparoscopic converted to open standard Whipple with reconstruction of the portal vein utilizing synthetic material and subsequent repair of umbilical hernia on 8/19/2020.  Post op course included:
•	Intra-op bile cultures returned positive for multi-drug resistant gram-negative bacilli – managed with cefepime, ciprofloxacin, and vancomycin.
•	Superficial site infection - drainage from abdominal midline incision – sutures placed; amoxicillin and cefadroxil 
•	Occlusion of the SMV graft – started high intensity heparin drip that was transitioned to Lovenox
•	Acute kidney injury – managed medically with Lasix and avoidance of further nephrotoxic medications.
•	Atrial Fibrillation with rapid ventricular response – started diltiazem
•	Thrombocytopenia; multifactorial – transfused platelets intermittently
•	Anemia – transfused red blood cells intermittently
•	Hypokalemia
•	 Ileus
•	Diarrhea – pancreatic enzyme insufficiency CREON
•	Ascites
•	Total parental nutrition

Participant went the the ER due to hyperglycemia. This came as a result of medication mismanagement due to participant's cognitive impairment. He mistook his dementia medication for his vitamins, in addition to being prescribed the wrong dose of metformin due to pharmacy error (500mg vs. 1000mg). This resulted in a significant decrease in appetite. SP reports he didn't eat for 4 days. While at the ER, he was prescribed Glimepiride (1mg PO QD) to reduce glucose levels. SP reports that his glucose levels are still high (~200mg/dL), but is being managed by the glimepiride. He is also now taking correct doses of dementia medication and metformin. Pt has a medical hx of Type II diabetes, diagnosed in 2008.

11/23/22: AE written based on medical records. I have not been able to speak to SP about what's going on. Pt has some vision complaints in his right eye that started 9/16/22 that he told his neurologist about on 9/30/22. He's also been less energetic since mid-August of 2022, reporting that he is sleeping more. Neurologist ordered an MRI that was scheduled for 11/2/22 without contrast. Patient's wife and SP reported to her PCP that he is having increased difficulty ambulating and weakness. The MRI on 11/2 revealed an occipital mass and he was referred to neurosurgery for an appointment on 11/3/22 to discuss treatment and etiology. Pt had a second MRI with contrast on 11/3/22 that confirmed Prescence of a mass that was 7x5.4.5cm in the Left occipital lobe with extension along the temporal parietal junction. There is mild surrounding edema.  The ependymal surface is involved.  Contrast-enhancement appears to extend into the proximal left splenium of the corpus callosum.  The appearance is much more consistent with high-grade glioma, with metastatic disease and lymphoma being considered much less likely.  The neurosurgeon and his oncologist determined that it would be most reasonable to pursue a symptom management strategy. Pt is clinically declining quickly and is now spending most of his time in bed as well as having significant challenges with proprioception, visuospatial awareness, and bladder control. Patient was started on Dexamethasone to 4 mg PO daily with ongoing use of Pepcid to prevent GERD from steroids that were started on 11/6/22. AEHCOMM:
Participant went to ED on 7/27/2020 for evaluation of abdominal discomfort and urinary retention. Her urinalysis with microscopic findings were consistent with UTI (resulted 07/27/20: 2+ blood, positive nitrite, 3+ leukocyte esterase, Packed WBCs, 4+ bacteria). A Foley catheter was inserted, and greater than 1000 mL of urine output was collected in the bag. The pt. immediately had relief of her abdominal discomfort. The ED care team felt her bladder distention was caused by underlying UTI which was likely contributing to her constipation (please also see IHA #16-chronic constipation). She was given a single dose of IV Rocephin in the ED on
07/27/20. She had no evidence for severe sepsis or septic shock, and the pt. was comfortable to be discharged with a catheter and oral antibiotics (cephalexin 500 mg, q8h for 7 days). The pt. took her cephalexin as prescribed, 500mg every 8 hours from 7/28/20 – 8/3/2020. The indwelling catheter was removed on 08/03/2020; no repeat indwelling catheter was placed after 08/03/2020. See attached for more information.

She was seen and followed by palliative care throughout this time. On 2/17/22, she was taken to the ED for frequent falls and abdominal pain in her left lower quadrant. She was brought into the ED with a report of an unknown amount of falls at the independent living facility where she lived with her husband. Her husband was the person who called EMS because he didn't feel he could care for her anymore and he thinks she needs a higher level of care. Given her presentation at the ED, the provider facilitated extensive conversations with both the palliative care team and the patient’s daughter Karen in establishing goals of care. The family decided to establish care with hospice starting the following day (2/18/22). The participant’s health quickly declined when she was on hospice and died on 3/14/22. Given how brief the period was from placing the patient on hospice to her death, the family experienced complicated grieving. Study team will follow-up with participant's family at a later time

RD 06/24/2022: There was concern on CT head/brain for ventriculomegaly and NPH; however, the resident had been informed that enlarged ventricles has been present as part of the ongoing Alzheimer's disease and that the diagnosis of NPH was inappropriate. MRI brain on 06/22/2022 showed chronic microvascular ischemic changes and hydrocephalus was unlikely to be due to NPH.  Pt. was seen by Dr George Gonzalez, neurologist, and he agreed that this was not NPH.  UA was clear, C & S is awaited. He did receive a dose of Rocephin. From neurology standpoint, pt. has been discharged. 06/23/2022 the spouse reported that he was walking well, fully oriented and not confused. Pt. was diagnosed with a transient ischemic attack.  He is presently still in the hospital with plans for discharge later today, 06/24/2022.  Pt. will be following up with our clinic on an outpatient basis. Pt. has a history of TIA in 03/2014; atrial fibrillation onset 04/2012; myocardial infarction 10/2017; left heart catheterization with stent placement 10/2019; right carotid endarterectomy 04/2014; coronary artery disease 2012. 7/5/2022 MTG: Upon review of his hospital chart it was noted that the patient was discharged on 06/23/2022 from the hospital.

A surgical site infection with sinus tract to laminectomy was confirmed from the 03/28/2022 dressing change, cultures growing Corynebacterium striatum. A  superior vena cava PICC line was placed on 03/29/2022 and infection treatment with IV vancomycin 750mg/150 mL BID started 03/29/2022, prescribed to continue through 04/22/2022.
